{"title_page": "British Lion (album)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = British Lion\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| cover      = Steve Harris - British Lion.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 24 September 2012\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     = *Monkey Puzzle, Suffolk, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 2, 4, 9)</small>\n*Purple Studio, Norwich, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 1, 2 7)</small>\n*BL Studios, Harlow, UK <small>(back tracks & vocal track 10)</small>\n*Barnyard Studios, Harlow, Essex <small>(back tracks)</small>\n*Algarve Studio, Faro, Portugal <small>(back tracks)</small>\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref name=\"kerrang lion\">{{cite journal | title = Beyond the Beast | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 15 September 2012 | first = George | last = Garner | issue = 1432 | pages = 22\u201327}}</ref>\n| length     = 52:11\n| label      = *[[EMI]] <small>(International edition)</small>\n*[[Universal Music Enterprises|UME]] <small>(US edition)</small>\n| producer   = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] released their album with [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], best known as the bassist and primary songwriter for the British heavy metal band [[Iron Maiden]]. The album was announced on 18 July 2012 and released on 24 September.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Announces First Ever Solo Album ''British Lion'' |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223010938/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |archivedate=23 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] announced their second album titled [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]] on 31 October 2019 and released it on 17 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/steve-harriss-british-lion-announce-second-album-the-burning|title=Steve Harris's British Lion announce second album The Burning|last=October 2019|first=Fraser Lewry31|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]], critics published reviews on their thoughts of the album. '''Metal Planet Music''' voiced that \"the first thing that strikes you is the music, great hard rock with melody and class, but it\u2019s the heart and emotion that will stay with you long after the last note rings out. Coming eight years after their debut, \u2018'''''The Burning'''''\u2019 is the second album by [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] and the [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] led quintet have made a record that is at once modern, nostalgic and timeless\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalplanetmusic.com/2020/01/gig-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review : British Lion \u2013 \u2018The Burning|last=Authoradmin|date=2020-01-22|website=Metal Planet Music|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Kerrang!]] mainly spoke upon the vocals of the album stating that \"the band\u2019s debut was rather a baptism of fire for singer '''Richard Taylor''', who had to weather some predictable yet redundant criticisms comparing him to [[Bruce Dickinson]] from Steve\u2019s \u201cother\u201d band. He sings like he has a point to prove throughout '''''The Burning'''''. A telling sign of the frontman\u2019s burgeoning confidence comes on '''Elysium''' \u2013 a song that boasts a killer chorus but an even better final passage, as he belts out a series of absolutely massive sustained notes over a swelling choral section. Equally impressive is his ability to extract emotion from a song. Whether he\u2019s communing with lost souls on '''Lightning''' or offering a consolatory ear on closer '''Native Son''', he often brings a moving sense of fragility to the fore. Clearly, this particular lion has more at its disposal than claws alone\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review: British Lion \u2013 The Burning|website=Kerrang!|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] rated the album a 4/5, and believes \"'''''The Burning''''' sounds vastly more punchy and powerful than its predecessor, while also giving the distinct impression that '''British Lion''' have evolved into a fiery and characterful ensemble with a strong identity of their own\". The review continued by stating that \"we are still firmly in traditional rock territory here, and [[Steve Harris (musician)|Harris]]\u2019s love of [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and [[Golden Earring]] remains as cheerfully conspicuous as ever, but thanks to a brighter, breezier sound and unmistakable hints of looseness and swagger, everything from the briskly uplifting title track to the brooding hulk of '''Bible Black''' sparkles with freshness and weirdly youthful vigour\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/british-lion-arrys-other-army-return-on-sizzling-form|title=British Lion: \u2018Arry\u2019s other army return on sizzling form|last=January 2020|first=Dom Lawson 17|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''Metal Temple''' deemed the album a 9/10 saying '''\"''The Burning''\"''' is just what a sophomore album should be. A continuation, with enthusiasm, growth and development. [[Steve Harris (musician)|Harris]] is his usual subdued bass thumping brilliance. '''Hawkins''' and '''Leslie's''' dual guitar attack is on point, '''Dawson's''' drums precise and well deftly executed. '''Taylor's''' vocals add a final layer of confidence to the formula that seals the deal. '''British Lion's \"''The Burning''\"''' is refreshing in it's telling of the story, and hints of even better tales in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metal-temple.com/site/catalogues/entry/reviews/cd_3/b_2/british-lion-the.htm|title=Metal-Temple.com :: British Lion \u2013 The Burning (CD Review)|last=bkarr272|website=www.metal-temple.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''KNAC''' stated that \"good things come to those who wait\". \"'''''The Burning''''' is a molten magma of soaring and even syncopated vocals that hover over sometimes haunting neo-Celtic melodies and sometimes epic, wistful and melancholic lyrical themes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=35238|title=British Lion - The Burning album review|last=|first=|date=|website=KNAC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15/04/2020}}</ref>\n\n=[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion Band]]=\nFollowing the initial announcement of the album's release in July 2012, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' revealed that the project originated with a band, named [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]], which Harris had been mentoring in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |title=Maiden's Harris announces solo album |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=18 July 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119104531/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 }}</ref> Harris confirmed this during an interview with ''Classic Rock'' the following month, explaining that he became involved after \"Graham Leslie [guitar] came to me with a cassette of songs... and I thought they were really good, so I said I\u2019d try to help his band do something. I ended up managing them and producing them and writing with them.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |title=Exclusive: Iron Maiden\u2019s Steve Harris talks about his British Lion solo project |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Brannigan |first=Paul |date=27 August 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020112709/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |archivedate=20 October 2013 }}</ref> After the original band split up, he \"kept in touch with Richie [Taylor, vocals] and Graham, and then Richie was working with another guitarist called David Hawkins, who's a really talented guy, and so we started writing songs together.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> After several years of work, due to Harris being occupied with Iron Maiden, the album ultimately consists of \"six songs written with Richie and David, there's one with just me and Richie, and the others are me, Richie, Graham and a couple of other guys that were around at the time.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> In an interview published by ''[[Kerrang!]]'' in September, Harris said that he considers [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] \"more of a side-project\" than a solo record.<ref name=\"kerrang lion\"/>\n\nStylistically, Harris argues that the record is \"more mainstream rock than metal, very British sounding, very 70s-influenced and quite commercial\u2026 but good commercial. There's all kinds of stuff going on, with nods to [[the Who]] and [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and some classic British rock bands, but it's not the progressive rock album some might be expecting.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> During his appearance on ''[[That Metal Show]]'' in September 2012, Harris revealed that he tried a number of bass-playing techniques which he would not do with Iron Maiden, such as letting his strings \"go dead\".<ref>{{cite episode | title = Iron Maiden | series = [[That Metal Show]] | serieslink =  | credits = [[Eddie Trunk]], [[Jim Florentine]], [[Don Jamieson (comedian)|Don Jamieson]] (starring) | network = [[VH1 Classic]] | station = | location = Los Angeles | airdate = 22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHarris stated that he intends to tour the release at some stage, remarking that, although \"there are no shows arranged yet\", \"I know we\u2019ll be playing clubs, which is great because I\u2019ve not played clubs for years\", and that he intends to release a follow up album in the future.<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> A European club tour, taking place in February and March, was eventually announced on 10 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kielty |first=Martin |title=Steve Harris announces solo UK tour |url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215175706/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2013 |work=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |accessdate=10 January 2013 |date=10 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Taking ''British Lion'' On The Road \u2013 \"It's Exciting, Going Back to the Roots, And It's Going To Be Fantastic\"|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/196789|work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA music video for the song \"This Is My God\" was released on 2 October 2012,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |title=Steve Harris reveals his God |accessdate=2 October 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=2 October 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006025045/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |archivedate=6 October 2012 }}</ref> followed by a video for \"Us Against the World\" on 28 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iron Maiden Bassist Releases 'Us Against The World' Video|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=182906|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=28 November 2012|date=28 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 56/100<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web| title = ''British Lion'' Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More| work = [[Metacritic]]| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]| url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/british-lion| accessdate = 16 August 2013}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About.com\">{{cite web | url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/Steve-Harris-British-Lion-Review.htm | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' Review | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | last = Bowar | first = Chad | publisher = [[About.com]]}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name= \"AM\">{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2568550|first=James Christopher|last=Monger|title=Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion''|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Artistdirect]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"artistdirect\">{{cite web|title=Steve Harris ''British Lion'' Album Review \u2013 5 out of 5 stars|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/steve-harris-british-lion-album-review-5-out-of-5-stars/10254241|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|accessdate=2 April 2013|author=Rick Florino|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]''\n| rev4Score = 7/10<ref name=\"CR review\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Jon | last = Hotten | issue = 176 | pages = 96 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185549/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev5Score = 3/10<ref name=\"drowned in sound\">{{cite web | url = http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17242/reviews/4145501?ticker | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 18 September 2012 | first = Ryan | last = Drever | publisher = [[Drowned in Sound]] | date = 18 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Kerrang!\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 5 September 2012 | first = Nick | last = Ruskell | issue = 1431 | pages = 52 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg | accessdate = 8 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185739/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Metal Hammer]]''\n| rev7Score = 8/10<ref name=\"MHreview\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dom | last = Lawson | issue = 236 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185637/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev8Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ezell|first=Brice|title=Steve Harris: ''British Lion''|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164520-steve-harris-british-lion/|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=12 November 2012|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Record Collector\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Record Collector]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dayal | last = Patterson | issue = 406 | url = http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/british-lion | accessdate = 24 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]''\n| rev10Score = 3/5<ref name=\"Revolver\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | title = Review: Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 25 September 2012 | last = Grow | first = Kory | date = 25 September 2012 | magazine = [[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120927032453/http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | archive-date = 27 September 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of August 2013, ''British Lion'' holds a score of 56 at the aggregate review site [[Metacritic]], indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta\"/> ''[[Record Collector]]'' awarded the album 3/5 and stated that \"though it's not entirely a chore to listen to, it is probably not memorable enough to appeal far outside of that circle [of Iron Maiden fans]\".<ref name=\"Record Collector\"/> ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' also gave it a score of 3/5, although they praised the \"cohesive\" song-writing and referred to Taylor as \"a compelling hard-rock singer\".<ref name=\"Revolver\"/> [[AllMusic]] gave it a score of 2.5/5, deeming it \"a serviceable slab of unpretentious yet utterly forgettable '80s retro-metal that adheres to every clich\u00e9 in the book\".<ref name= \"AM\"/> Although they called it \"a solid \u201870s style hard rock effort\", [[About.com]] criticised some songs for being \"nothing but filler.\"<ref name=\"About.com\"/>\n\n''[[Kerrang!]]'' deemed it \"a brilliant album\", describing it as \"the sound of an incredibly talented songwriter stepping outside of what he'd normally do and indulging himself in something a bit different with a group of excellent musicians.\"<ref name=\"Kerrang!\"/> ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' were also very positive towards the release, praising the \"infectious re-imaginings of the [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and [[Thin Lizzy]] albums that inspired their creator as a kid,\" concluding that \"This is a big hearted and ferocious triumph.\"<ref name=\"MHreview\"/> Although they criticised the album's lyrics, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' complimented vocalist Richard Taylor and guitarist Graham Leslie, concluding that \"''British Lion'' is an album that is both exactly what you'd expect, and far better than that.\"<ref name=\"CR review\"/> [[Artistdirect]] awarded it full marks, stating that \"As far as songwriters go, [Harris is] on the level with [[Jimmy Page]] and [[Tony Iommi]], and his new album, ''British Lion'', proves that tenfold\".<ref name=\"artistdirect\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs are written by [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], Richard Taylor, David Hawkins unless otherwise noted.\n{{tracklist\n| title1   = This Is My God\n| writer1   = \n| length1  = 4:57\n| title2   = Lost Worlds\n| writer2   =\n| length2  = 4:58\n| title3   = Karma Killer\n| writer3   = \n| length3  = 5:29\n| title4   = Us Against the World\n| writer4   = \n| length4  = 4:12\n| title5   = The Chosen Ones\n| writer5   = Harris, Taylor\n| length5  = 6:27\n| title6   = A World Without Heaven\n| writer6   = Barry Fitzgibbon, Harris, Grahame Leslie, Gary Liederman, Ian Roberts, Taylor\n| length6  = 7:02\n| title7   = Judas\n| writer7   = \n| length7  = 4:58\n| title8   = Eyes of the Young\n| writer8   = Harris, Leslie, Roberts, Taylor\n| length8  = 5:25\n| title9   = These Are the Hands\n| writer9   = \n| length9  = 4:28\n| title10  = The Lesson\n| writer10  = \n| length10 = 4:15\n| total_length  = 52:11\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] \u2013 bass guitar, production\n*Richard Taylor \u2013 lead vocals, production\n*David Hawkins \u2013 guitars, keyboards (all tracks except 5, 6 and 8), production, recording\n*Grahame Leslie \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Simon Dawson \u2013 drums (tracks 2, 4 and 9)\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*Barry Fitzgibbon \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Ian Roberts \u2013 drums (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Richard Cook \u2013 drums (tracks 1, 3 and 7)\n*[[Kevin Shirley]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ade Emsley \u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Steve+Harris&titel=British+Lion&cat=a | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | publisher = Austriancharts.at | accessdate = 3 October 2012 | work = [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]| language = German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 66\n|-\n|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart (Flanders)]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ultratop.be/nl/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20121013 | title = Charts Vlaanderen: 200 Albums 13/10/2012 | accessdate = 15 October 2012 | date = 13 October 2013 | publisher = [[Ultratop]]| language = Dutch}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 180\n|-\n|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart (Wallonia)]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ultratop.be/fr/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20120929 | title = Charts Wallonie: 200 Albums 29/09/2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 29 September 2012 | publisher = [[Ultratop]] | language = French}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|72\n|-\n|[[The Official Finnish Charts|Finnish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://finnishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=201239 | title = Album Top 50- Week 29/2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = Finnishcharts.com|work=[[The Official Finnish Charts]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://lescharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20120929 | title = Les Charts \u2013 Album Top 100, 29/09/2012 | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | date = 6 October 2012 | publisher = Lescharts.com|work=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] | language = French}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 85\n|-\n|[[Media Control Charts|German Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.officialcharts.de/album.asp?artist=Steve+Harris&title=British+Lion&country=de | title = Steve Harris, ''British Lion'' H\u00f6chstposition |date= 2 October 2012 | accessdate = 2 October 2012 | publisher = Charts.de| work=[[Media Control Charts]] | language = German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 67\n|-\n|[[Federation of the Italian Music Industry|Italian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_artisti.php?anno=%202012&mese=10&id=427 | title = FIMI Artisti Classifica settimanale dal 24/09/2012 al 30/09/2012 | accessdate = 4 October 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] | language = Italian | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150518084438/http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_artisti.php?anno=%202012&mese=10&id=427# | archive-date = 18 May 2015 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 39\n|-\n|[[VG-lista|Norwegian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://norwegiancharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=201240 | title = VG Lista \u2013 Album Top 40, Week 40/2012 | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | publisher = Norwegiancharts.com|work=[[VG-lista]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 30\n|-\n|[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|Spanish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.org/files/listassemanales/albumes/top%20100%20albumes%20%28publicar%29_w39.2012.pdf |title=Top 100 Albumes Semana 39: del 24.09.2012 al 30.09.2012 |accessdate=3 October 2012 |date=30 September 2012 |publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]] |language=Spanish |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6B8vyeRF9?url=http://www.promusicae.org/files/listassemanales/albumes/top%20100%20albumes%20%28publicar%29_w39.2012.pdf |archivedate=3 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 63\n|-\n|[[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"sweden\">{{cite web | url = http://swedishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20121005 | title = Sverigetopplistan \u2013 Albums Top 60, 5 October 2012  | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | date = 5 October 2012 | publisher = [[Sverigetopplistan]] | language = Swedish}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18\n|-\n|[[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://hitparade.ch/weekchart.asp?cat=a&date=20121007&year=2012 | title = Schweizer Hitparade \u2013 Alben Top 100: 07.10.2012 | accessdate = 3 October 2012 | date = 3 October 2012 | publisher = [[Swiss Music Charts]] | language = German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 40\n|-\n|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2012-10-06/ | title = Top 40 Official UK Albums Archive 6 October 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|[[UK Rock & Metal Singles and Albums Charts|UK Rock & Metal Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/11/2012-10-06/ | title = Top 40 Rock & Metal Albums Archive 6 October 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref>{{cite web | url = {{BillboardURLbyName|artist=steve harris|chart=all}} | title = Steve Harris ''Billboard'' Albums | accessdate = 23 February 2013 | work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 138\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 debut albums]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal albums by English artists]]\n", "text_old": "= [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] =\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = British Lion\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| cover      = Steve Harris - British Lion.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 24 September 2012\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     = *Monkey Puzzle, Suffolk, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 2, 4, 9)</small>\n*Purple Studio, Norwich, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 1, 2 7)</small>\n*BL Studios, Harlow, UK <small>(back tracks & vocal track 10)</small>\n*Barnyard Studios, Harlow, Essex <small>(back tracks)</small>\n*Algarve Studio, Faro, Portugal <small>(back tracks)</small>\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref name=\"kerrang lion\">{{cite journal | title = Beyond the Beast | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 15 September 2012 | first = George | last = Garner | issue = 1432 | pages = 22\u201327}}</ref>\n| length     = 52:11\n| label      = *[[EMI]] <small>(International edition)</small>\n*[[Universal Music Enterprises|UME]] <small>(US edition)</small>\n| producer   = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] released their album with [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], best known as the bassist and primary songwriter for the British heavy metal band [[Iron Maiden]]. The album was announced on 18 July 2012 and released on 24 September.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Announces First Ever Solo Album ''British Lion'' |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223010938/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |archivedate=23 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] announced their second album titled [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]] on the 31st of October 2019 and released it on the 17th of January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/steve-harriss-british-lion-announce-second-album-the-burning|title=Steve Harris's British Lion announce second album The Burning|last=October 2019|first=Fraser Lewry31|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]], critics published reviews on their thoughts of the album. '''Metal Planet Music''' voiced that \"the first thing that strikes you is the music, great hard rock with melody and class, but it\u2019s the heart and emotion that will stay with you long after the last note rings out. Coming eight years after their debut, \u2018'''''The Burning'''''\u2019 is the second album by [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] and the [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] led quintet have made a record that is at once modern, nostalgic and timeless\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalplanetmusic.com/2020/01/gig-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review : British Lion \u2013 \u2018The Burning|last=Authoradmin|date=2020-01-22|website=Metal Planet Music|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Kerrang!]] mainly spoke upon the vocals of the album stating that \"the band\u2019s debut was rather a baptism of fire for singer '''Richard Taylor''', who had to weather some predictable yet redundant criticisms comparing him to [[Bruce Dickinson]] from Steve\u2019s \u201cother\u201d band. He sings like he has a point to prove throughout '''''The Burning'''''. A telling sign of the frontman\u2019s burgeoning confidence comes on '''Elysium''' \u2013 a song that boasts a killer chorus but an even better final passage, as he belts out a series of absolutely massive sustained notes over a swelling choral section. Equally impressive is his ability to extract emotion from a song. Whether he\u2019s communing with lost souls on '''Lightning''' or offering a consolatory ear on closer '''Native Son''', he often brings a moving sense of fragility to the fore. Clearly, this particular lion has more at its disposal than claws alone\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review: British Lion \u2013 The Burning|website=Kerrang!|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] rated the album a 4/5, and believes \"'''''The Burning''''' sounds vastly more punchy and powerful than its predecessor, while also giving the distinct impression that '''British Lion''' have evolved into a fiery and characterful ensemble with a strong identity of their own\". The review continued by stating that \"we are still firmly in traditional rock territory here, and [[Steve Harris (musician)|Harris]]\u2019s love of [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and [[Golden Earring]] remains as cheerfully conspicuous as ever, but thanks to a brighter, breezier sound and unmistakable hints of looseness and swagger, everything from the briskly uplifting title track to the brooding hulk of '''Bible Black''' sparkles with freshness and weirdly youthful vigour\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/british-lion-arrys-other-army-return-on-sizzling-form|title=British Lion: \u2018Arry\u2019s other army return on sizzling form|last=January 2020|first=Dom Lawson 17|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''Metal Temple''' deemed the album a 9/10 saying '''\u201c''The Burning''\u201d''' is just what a sophomore album should be. A continuation, with enthusiasm, growth and development. [[Steve Harris (musician)|Harris]] is his usual subdued bass thumping brilliance. '''Hawkins''' and '''Leslie's''' dual guitar attack is on point, '''Dawson's''' drums precise and well deftly executed. '''Taylor's''' vocals add a final layer of confidence to the formula that seals the deal. '''British Lion's \u201c''The Burning''\u201d''' is refreshing in it's telling of the story, and hints of even better tales in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metal-temple.com/site/catalogues/entry/reviews/cd_3/b_2/british-lion-the.htm|title=Metal-Temple.com :: British Lion \u2013 The Burning (CD Review)|last=bkarr272|website=www.metal-temple.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''KNAC''' stated that \"good things come to those who wait\". \"'''''The Burning''''' is a molten magma of soaring and even syncopated vocals that hover over sometimes haunting neo-Celtic melodies and sometimes epic, wistful and melancholic lyrical themes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=35238|title=British Lion - The Burning album review|last=|first=|date=|website=KNAC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15/04/2020}}</ref>\n\n=[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion Band]]=\nFollowing the initial announcement of the album's release in July 2012, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' revealed that the project originated with a band, named [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]], which Harris had been mentoring in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |title=Maiden's Harris announces solo album |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=18 July 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119104531/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 }}</ref> Harris confirmed this during an interview with ''Classic Rock'' the following month, explaining that he became involved after \"Graham Leslie [guitar] came to me with a cassette of songs... and I thought they were really good, so I said I\u2019d try to help his band do something. I ended up managing them and producing them and writing with them.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |title=Exclusive: Iron Maiden\u2019s Steve Harris talks about his British Lion solo project |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Brannigan |first=Paul |date=27 August 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020112709/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |archivedate=20 October 2013 }}</ref> After the original band split up, he \"kept in touch with Richie [Taylor, vocals] and Graham, and then Richie was working with another guitarist called David Hawkins, who's a really talented guy, and so we started writing songs together.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> After several years of work, due to Harris being occupied with Iron Maiden, the album ultimately consists of \"six songs written with Richie and David, there's one with just me and Richie, and the others are me, Richie, Graham and a couple of other guys that were around at the time.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> In an interview published by ''[[Kerrang!]]'' in September, Harris said that he considers [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] \"more of a side-project\" than a solo record.<ref name=\"kerrang lion\"/>\n\nStylistically, Harris argues that the record is \"more mainstream rock than metal, very British sounding, very 70s-influenced and quite commercial\u2026 but good commercial. There's all kinds of stuff going on, with nods to [[the Who]] and [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and some classic British rock bands, but it's not the progressive rock album some might be expecting.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> During his appearance on ''[[That Metal Show]]'' in September 2012, Harris revealed that he tried a number of bass-playing techniques which he would not do with Iron Maiden, such as letting his strings \"go dead\".<ref>{{cite episode | title = Iron Maiden | series = [[That Metal Show]] | serieslink =  | credits = [[Eddie Trunk]], [[Jim Florentine]], [[Don Jamieson (comedian)|Don Jamieson]] (starring) | network = [[VH1 Classic]] | station = | location = Los Angeles | airdate = 22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHarris stated that he intends to tour the release at some stage, remarking that, although \"there are no shows arranged yet\", \"I know we\u2019ll be playing clubs, which is great because I\u2019ve not played clubs for years\", and that he intends to release a follow up album in the future.<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> A European club tour, taking place in February and March, was eventually announced on 10 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kielty |first=Martin |title=Steve Harris announces solo UK tour |url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215175706/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2013 |work=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |accessdate=10 January 2013 |date=10 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Taking ''British Lion'' On The Road \u2013 \"It's Exciting, Going Back to the Roots, And It's Going To Be Fantastic\"|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/196789|work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA music video for the song \"This Is My God\" was released on 2 October 2012,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |title=Steve Harris reveals his God |accessdate=2 October 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=2 October 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006025045/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |archivedate=6 October 2012 }}</ref> followed by a video for \"Us Against the World\" on 28 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iron Maiden Bassist Releases 'Us Against The World' Video|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=182906|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=28 November 2012|date=28 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 56/100<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web| title = ''British Lion'' Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More| work = [[Metacritic]]| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]| url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/british-lion| accessdate = 16 August 2013}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About.com\">{{cite web | url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/Steve-Harris-British-Lion-Review.htm | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' Review | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | last = Bowar | first = Chad | publisher = [[About.com]]}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name= \"AM\">{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2568550|first=James Christopher|last=Monger|title=Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion''|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Artistdirect]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"artistdirect\">{{cite web|title=Steve Harris ''British Lion'' Album Review \u2013 5 out of 5 stars|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/steve-harris-british-lion-album-review-5-out-of-5-stars/10254241|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|accessdate=2 April 2013|author=Rick Florino|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]''\n| rev4Score = 7/10<ref name=\"CR review\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Jon | last = Hotten | issue = 176 | pages = 96 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185549/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev5Score = 3/10<ref name=\"drowned in sound\">{{cite web | url = http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17242/reviews/4145501?ticker | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 18 September 2012 | first = Ryan | last = Drever | publisher = [[Drowned in Sound]] | date = 18 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Kerrang!\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 5 September 2012 | first = Nick | last = Ruskell | issue = 1431 | pages = 52 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg | accessdate = 8 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185739/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Metal Hammer]]''\n| rev7Score = 8/10<ref name=\"MHreview\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dom | last = Lawson | issue = 236 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185637/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev8Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ezell|first=Brice|title=Steve Harris: ''British Lion''|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164520-steve-harris-british-lion/|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=12 November 2012|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Record Collector\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Record Collector]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dayal | last = Patterson | issue = 406 | url = http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/british-lion | accessdate = 24 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]''\n| rev10Score = 3/5<ref name=\"Revolver\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | title = Review: Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 25 September 2012 | last = Grow | first = Kory | date = 25 September 2012 | magazine = [[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120927032453/http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | archive-date = 27 September 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of August 2013, ''British Lion'' holds a score of 56 at the aggregate review site [[Metacritic]], indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta\"/> ''[[Record Collector]]'' awarded the album 3/5 and stated that \"though it's not entirely a chore to listen to, it is probably not memorable enough to appeal far outside of that circle [of Iron Maiden fans]\".<ref name=\"Record Collector\"/> ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' also gave it a score of 3/5, although they praised the \"cohesive\" song-writing and referred to Taylor as \"a compelling hard-rock singer\".<ref name=\"Revolver\"/> [[AllMusic]] gave it a score of 2.5/5, deeming it \"a serviceable slab of unpretentious yet utterly forgettable '80s retro-metal that adheres to every clich\u00e9 in the book\".<ref name= \"AM\"/> Although they called it \"a solid \u201870s style hard rock effort\", [[About.com]] criticised some songs for being \"nothing but filler.\"<ref name=\"About.com\"/>\n\n''[[Kerrang!]]'' deemed it \"a brilliant album\", describing it as \"the sound of an incredibly talented songwriter stepping outside of what he'd normally do and indulging himself in something a bit different with a group of excellent musicians.\"<ref name=\"Kerrang!\"/> ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' were also very positive towards the release, praising the \"infectious re-imaginings of the [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and [[Thin Lizzy]] albums that inspired their creator as a kid,\" concluding that \"This is a big hearted and ferocious triumph.\"<ref name=\"MHreview\"/> Although they criticised the album's lyrics, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' complimented vocalist Richard Taylor and guitarist Graham Leslie, concluding that \"''British Lion'' is an album that is both exactly what you'd expect, and far better than that.\"<ref name=\"CR review\"/> [[Artistdirect]] awarded it full marks, stating that \"As far as songwriters go, [Harris is] on the level with [[Jimmy Page]] and [[Tony Iommi]], and his new album, ''British Lion'', proves that tenfold\".<ref name=\"artistdirect\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs are written by [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], Richard Taylor, David Hawkins unless otherwise noted.\n{{tracklist\n| title1   = This Is My God\n| writer1   = \n| length1  = 4:57\n| title2   = Lost Worlds\n| writer2   =\n| length2  = 4:58\n| title3   = Karma Killer\n| writer3   = \n| length3  = 5:29\n| title4   = Us Against the World\n| writer4   = \n| length4  = 4:12\n| title5   = The Chosen Ones\n| writer5   = Harris, Taylor\n| length5  = 6:27\n| title6   = A World Without Heaven\n| writer6   = Barry Fitzgibbon, Harris, Grahame Leslie, Gary Liederman, Ian Roberts, Taylor\n| length6  = 7:02\n| title7   = Judas\n| writer7   = \n| length7  = 4:58\n| title8   = Eyes of the Young\n| writer8   = Harris, Leslie, Roberts, Taylor\n| length8  = 5:25\n| title9   = These Are the Hands\n| writer9   = \n| length9  = 4:28\n| title10  = The Lesson\n| writer10  = \n| length10 = 4:15\n| total_length  = 52:11\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] \u2013 bass guitar, production\n*Richard Taylor \u2013 lead vocals, production\n*David Hawkins \u2013 guitars, keyboards (all tracks except 5, 6 and 8), production, recording\n*Grahame Leslie \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Simon Dawson \u2013 drums (tracks 2, 4 and 9)\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*Barry Fitzgibbon \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Ian Roberts \u2013 drums (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Richard Cook \u2013 drums (tracks 1, 3 and 7)\n*[[Kevin Shirley]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ade Emsley \u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Steve+Harris&titel=British+Lion&cat=a | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | publisher = Austriancharts.at | accessdate = 3 October 2012 | work = [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]| language = German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 66\n|-\n|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart (Flanders)]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ultratop.be/nl/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20121013 | title = Charts Vlaanderen: 200 Albums 13/10/2012 | accessdate = 15 October 2012 | date = 13 October 2013 | publisher = [[Ultratop]]| language = Dutch}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 180\n|-\n|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart (Wallonia)]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ultratop.be/fr/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20120929 | title = Charts Wallonie: 200 Albums 29/09/2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 29 September 2012 | publisher = [[Ultratop]] | language = French}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|72\n|-\n|[[The Official Finnish Charts|Finnish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://finnishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=201239 | title = Album Top 50- Week 29/2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012